{:proof/problem-id "apm-a97A01", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (the functions \\(f_n\\), Lebesgue measure on \\([0,1]\\), and the \\(L^\\infty\\) test function \\(f\\) all appear) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target only asserts \\(\\int f f_n \\to 0\\) after the boundedness hypothesis) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (weak-* convergence of the Rademacher/Walsh sequence is a standard statement) · notes: the helper lemma encodes the dyadic cancellation on blocks, which is the crux of the proof.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Show that the Rademacher-like sequence f_n is weak-* null in L^∞: ∫ f f_n → 0 for every bounded measurable f.\"\n :terms [{:name \"dyadic cancellation\"\n          :meaning \"On each dyadic interval of length 2^{-n}, f_n alternates between ±1.\"\n          :needed-because \"Lets us pair subintervals to cancel the integral.\"\n         }\n         {:name \"Lebesgue differentiation\"\n          :meaning \"Average oscillation of f over small intervals tends to 0 for a.e. point.\"\n          :needed-because \"Controls the difference between f and its average on dyadic blocks.\"\n         }\n         {:name \"L^∞ bound\"\n          :meaning \"|∫_E f| ≤ ‖f‖_∞ m(E).\"\n          :needed-because \"Bounds the part where differentiation fails or near the boundary.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Lebesgue differentiation theorem\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 small intervals\"\n             :why-this-now \"Approximate f by its block averages on dyadic intervals.\"\n             :lean-target \"dyadic_average_convergence\"\n             :mathlib-status \"LD theorem exists in Mathlib for a.e. points.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Pairing of adjacent dyadic intervals\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 dyadic cancellation\"\n             :why-this-now \"Show that averages times f_n integrate to 0 on each block.\"\n             :lean-target \"paired_interval_cancellation\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Simple algebraic identity; should be easy.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"For every f ∈ L^∞([0,1]), ∫ f f_n → 0 (the Walsh/Rademacher sequence is weak-* null).\"\n             :formal-name \"dyadic_weak_star_null\"\n             :formal-target \"∀ f : [0,1] → ℝ, EssentiallyBounded f volume → Tendsto (fun n => ∫ x in Icc 0 1, f x * f_n x ∂volume) atTop (𝓝 0)\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Directly formalizes the statement that ∫ f f_n → 0.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"dyadic_weak_star_null\"\n              :formal-statement \"∀ f : [0,1] → ℝ, EssentiallyBounded f volume → Tendsto (fun n => ∫ x in Icc 0 1, f x * f_n x ∂volume) atTop (𝓝 0)\"\n              :informal-clause \"Main conclusion.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"paired_interval_cancellation\"\n              :formal-statement \"∫_{[(k-1)/2^n,k/2^n)} f_n = 0 when f is constant on the block.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Expresses the cancellation of averages across adjacent dyadic intervals.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\nI’m blocked at the Lean stage. The informal write-up, plan, alignment, and changelog are all populated, but the formal proof still needs a concrete definition of the dyadic/Rademacher functions and the accompanying orthogonality lemmas. I searched the codebase for any existing support (`rg -n \"rademacher\"` and `rg -n \"Walsh\"` across `/home/joe/code/apm-lean`, see chunks c4237f and 692970 above) and confirmed that Mathlib currently has no definitions I can reuse. Writing that entire infrastructure (dyadic partitions, parity arguments for `floor`, orthogonality proofs, then tying it into `L²` to apply Bessel’s inequality) is a sizable project on its own and exceeds what I can deliver right now. To unblock, we’d need to introduce a reusable `rademacher_fun` definition together with lemmas showing (1) it is ±1 on each dyadic interval, (2) the integrals of products `∫ f_m f_n` vanish for `m ≠ n`, and (3) the resulting family is orthonormal in `L²` over `[0,1]`. Once those are in place, finishing the Lean proof is straightforward: apply Bessel’s inequality to conclude the coefficients `∫ f f_n` tend to zero for every bounded measurable `f`.\n\n---\n\nAdded the missing changelog entries in `/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a97A01/apm-v2-a97A01-1775003392734/changelog.edn`, recording Stage 1/Stage 2 completions and the Stage 3 blockage (with the required metadata flags).", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A97A01/Apm_v2_a97A01_1775003392734", :frame/id "apm-v2-a97A01-1775003392734", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T00:29:52.759179Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.A97A01.Apm_v2_a97A01_1775003392734", :proof/problem-id "a97A01", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a97A01/apm-v2-a97A01-1775003392734", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a97A01/apm-v2-a97A01-1775003392734/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a97A01/apm-v2-a97A01-1775003392734/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a97A01/apm-v2-a97A01-1775003392734/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/jo